<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-05-10T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-05-10T04:00:00-05:00" n="768" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d768">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.811/1115: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Peck</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-05-10T16:00:00+07:00">May 10,
                                    1939—4 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received May 10—10 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>322. The Embassy has today received a note from the Foreign Office
                            quoting a communication from the Military Affairs Commission to the
                            effect that the mouth of the West River in Kwangtung has been closed and
                            that the entrance and exit of Chinese and foreign vessels is
                            prohibited.</p>
                        <p>Repeat to Embassy at Peiping, Canton, Hong Kong. Latter please notify
                            American naval authorities and shippers at Canton and Hong Kong.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>